<div id="statement">
<h2><a title="about me" href="#about" id="statecreate">I create</a> clean, attractive <a title="about me" href="#about" id="interwebs">interactive websites</a>.</h2>

</div>


<div id="notice">
<p>I've read in a lot of places and been told by several people that it is poor design to not have a readily available navigation bar lurking above, below, and/or at my side.  The problem is that
it is impossible to get lost when you are constantly being told where you are and what's around you.  Is it possible that the feeling of discovering something new is significantly diminished 
when you arrived there by following constant road signs?
<br />
<b>This is an argument for getting lost:</b>  
<br />
	Go explore.  I leave you with new abilities and little direction.  Your mouse and buttons on your keyboard will do different 
	things in different places.  
	 </p>
</div> <!-- end notice -->

